•«The Twilight Mug»•

The first time I pulled a Twilight Mug out of the kiln after figuring out this combination of blue glazes and red clay I knew I had found “it”, and I’ve never looked back. They always tell you as an artist to try everything and keep experimenting with your craft until one day you will develop your own style… they’re so right. It took years of experimentation to figure out the perfect combination of developing my throwing skills (which I was determined to do pretty quickly after I realized hand building just is not for me), forms and shapes of pots, decoration techniques and the never ending glaze possibilities before I found exactly what I had been picturing in my head. Ceramics is a medium where there are endless possibilities of outcomes which makes it soooooo fun to play with and truly keeps your creativity flowing. It’s also not a medium for the faint of heart because anything can go wrong at any point of the process. Potters know to never fall in love with a piece until it’s out of the glaze firing. 

If you’ve been following along for a while you know that my beautiful dark red clay is being reformulated and is not available at the moment. My supplier said it would be about 8 weeks until this clay would be back in stock which has turned into 4 months 😭 I’ve pivoted to using another toasty reddish tan clay that I’ve used in the past but it just doesn’t give the same glaze results so this will be the last batch of Twilight Mugs (or anything with this glaze) for a while. I’m down to my last 2 boxes of my dark red clay and will be saving them for wholesale orders until my clay is back in stock. 

This latest batch is now available on my website and I will be bringing these mugs to May Markets with me until I run out. I’m putting it out into the universe that my dark red clay will be available sooner than later and I can get back to making the pieces that I love🤞🏼✨

New pieces came out of the kiln last night and they are all so perfect! 

Back in January my dark red clay became out of stock because the manufacturer was reformulating the recipe. Since I didn’t know exactly what that ingredient was I was honestly freaking out that this clay either wouldn’t be the same or my glazes wouldn’t look right on it anymore. Ceramics is like cooking vs baking… in cooking you can substitute ingredients and do a little more of this or a little less of that and your dinner will be fine, but in baking if you’re off your measurements even just a little it can completely ruin your dessert! 

I’m happy to say that my clay has been throwing exactly how it used to and my glazes look exactly how they used to which is such a big relief!!! I woke up in a full blown panic in the middle of the night because I was convinced the kiln load I’m firing right now wasn’t going to come out right 🤦🏼‍♀️ since I’m working with this white speckled clay again for a wholesale order I decided to just use up the two fresh boxes I had left and a whole 5 gallon bucket of reclaim. Because I normally use red clay I had to seriously clean my wheel, work table and all my tools to make the switch to white clay so I figured I better make it worth it! This is also the first time I’m firing an entire kiln load with just this white clay and it’s a little different than my red clay (for my potters, normally I do a straight cone 6 firing for my red but that’s too hot for this white clay so I’m doing a cone 5 with 15 minute hold to make sure the glazes fully develop). Please send all the good vibes to the kiln gods for a successful firing because I’m truly a little nervous about this one 🤞🏼🤞🏼🤞🏼 but the good news is that if it’s a good firing I’ll have plenty of white speckled pieces available for this Sundays SHOP UPDATE✨
